04179nam a22005295i 9781442625730DE-B159720210824034702.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||210824t20182017onc    fo  d z      eng d  a97814426257307 a10.3138/97814426257302doi  a(DE-B1597)498691  a(OCoLC)1054879670  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  aonccCA-ON 4aBL304b.B6813 2017eb 7aSOC0260002bisacsh04a201/.32231 aBouchard, Gerard, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aSocial Myths and Collective Imaginaries /cGerard Bouchard, Les Editions du Boreal. 1aToronto : bUniversity of Toronto Press, c[2018] 4c©2017  a1 online resource (176 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tIntroduction -- tChapter One. Myths and Collective Imaginaries -- tChapter Two. What is a Social Myth? -- tChapter Three. The Mythification Process -- tChapter Four. The Conditions for the Effectiveness of Myth -- tChapter Five. Social Myths: A Pyramidal Structure -- tGeneral Conclusion -- tNotes -- tBibliography -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aMyths are commonly associated with illusions or with deceptive, dangerous discourse, and are often perceived as largely the domain of premodern societies. But even in our post-industrial, technologically driven world, myths – Western or Eastern, ancient or modern, religious or scientific – are in fact powerful, pervasive forces. In Social Myths and Collective Imaginaries, Gérard Bouchard conceptualizes myths as vessels of sacred values that transcend the division between primitive and modern. Myths represent key elements of collective imaginaries, past and present. In all societies there are values and beliefs that hold sway over most of the population. Whether they come from religion, political institutions, or other sources, they enjoy exalted status and go largely unchallenged. These myths have the power to bring societies together as well as pull them apart. Yet the study of myth has been largely neglected by sociologists and other social scientists. Bouchard navigates this uncharted territory by addressing a number of fundamental questions: What is the place of myth in contemporary societies and in the relations between the cultural and the social? How do myths take form? From what do they draw their strength? How do they respond to shifting contexts? Myths matter, Bouchard argues, because of the energy they unleash, energy that enables a population to mobilize and rally around collective goals. At the same time myths work to alleviate collective anxiety and to meet the most pressing challenges facing a society. In this bold analysis, Bouchard challenges common assumptions and awakens us to the transcendent power of myth in our daily lives and in our shared aspirations.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 24. Aug 2021) 0aMyth. 0aSocial representations. 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / Sociology / General.2bisacsh1 aLes Editions du Boreal, , eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut1 aScott, Howard.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUniversity of Toronto Press Complete eBook-Package 2017z978311066594940uhttps://doi.org/10.3138/978144262573040uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781442625730423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/covers/9781442625730.jpg  a978-3-11-066594-9  University of Toronto Press Complete eBook-Package 2017b2017  aGBV-deGruyter-alles